      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The decision to intervene was fundamentally justified under the doctrine of the Responsibility to Protect (R2P), which mandates international action to prevent mass atrocities. The Gaddafi regime's actions against its own people clearly crossed the threshold into mass atrocity, giving the international community a moral and legal imperative to act. Critics often frame it as a pretext for regime change, but the immediate threat of a massacre was the primary, undeniable driver for the military action.",
      "source": "target",
